name: molly conger
tweet: extremely long set of instructions for public comment from the board of supervisors, including a reminder that clapping is NOT allowed. you’re supposed to “raise your hand” to show “support or opposition” to a speaker. 🤔🤷‍♀️

name: molly conger
tweet: the board of supervisors hasn’t looked at this since a joint session with the planning commission last year. the clerk says she knows there will be a lot of questions and comments & provides a brief overview of the project.  https://t.co/QF5gHyG2v7

name: molly conger
tweet: apparently a “center” is actually a defined term - the clerk clarified that it means “focal point,” rather than referring to a geographic location.    https://t.co/NYU4NvUJjP

name: molly conger
tweet: (county board of supervisors is NOT my usual meeting beat and she has no nameplate. i assume the woman at the end of the dais reading to the board is the clerk. my apologies if that’s not her title.)

name: molly conger
tweet: staff have recommended approval of the rezoning.  supervisor liz palmer asks the presenter, who just finished, to go back to the slide about “unfavorable” aspects of the rezoning.

name: molly conger
tweet: the woman presenting to the BOS is actually the senior planner - my apologies. at city meetings, staff presenting to council never sit at the dais. the seat on the far end of the dais is always the clerk at city council meetings.

name: molly conger
tweet: there are only two points on the “unfavorable factors” slide - added traffic on old lynchburg road and added students to cale elementary. as to the second factor:   https://t.co/J8JeGOfsjP

name: molly conger
tweet: supervisor ann mallek has questions about stormwater. the applicant has a total of 20 minutes to address the board.

name: molly conger
tweet: perhaps worthwhile to note that the southwood community is predominantly latinx. albemarle county is 80% white as of the last census, probably a little less now. every single member of the board of supervisors is white.

name: molly conger
tweet: this isn’t about building a community where none currently exists. this is about allowing an existing community to improve itself. this is about allowing a close knit community to engage in resident driven redevelopment.

name: molly conger
tweet: given that albemarle county census shows about 5,500 people self identify as hispanic & southwood is 1500 people, the overwhelming majority of whom are latinx, it’s fair to say this is probably the county’s largest latinx community.

name: molly conger
tweet: the applicant is presenting a lot of data.  the vast majority of families in the community fall below 80% AMI, with 80 families below 25% AMI. nearly 3/4 of families fall within the AMI range that qualifies them for habitat for humanity support.

name: molly conger
tweet: liz palmer is concerned that the 30ft buffer along old lynchburg rd is 30ft INCLUDING the trail, not 30ft + the trail. she’s brought this up twice already tonight. i hope that’s not concerning enough for her to go against both staff & the planning commission’s recommendation.

name: molly conger
tweet: supervisor normal dill asks how the resident designers choose where their houses will be and what they will look like & who leads that process.

name: molly conger
tweet: “we start with the dreaming side - what are you looking for? what do you want?” and the habitat team works with them to design something that fits their needs that they can afford.

name: molly conger
tweet: supervisor rick randolph says an earlier submission said residents prioritized leaving green space for their children, but comes in with what he seems to think is a gotcha about how the final proposal has less green space.

name: molly conger
tweet: the applicant says the resident design team ultimately sacrificed some green space for more single family units, while still leaving sufficient green space for kids.

name: molly conger
tweet: “does the applicant really believe that 4900 sq ft is adequate,” randolph asks about the recreational space. the applicant says there’s more focus on active recreational space vs the passive recreational space represented by that green space.

name: molly conger
tweet: again, let me remind you we aren’t talking about building a new community. we are talking about allowing a community that is currently old trailers with failing infrastructure to redevelop in a way envisioned by its residents. rick can take his concerns about soccer & shut up.

name: molly conger
tweet: rick randolph is clearly very hurt that there was a meeting to which BOS members were not invited.

name: molly conger
tweet: randolph is skeptical that habitat for humanity knows how to ensure units are affordable for poor people. which is... kind of their whole deal. i think they know how to do that.

name: molly conger
tweet: is he saying mixed income development is impossible because people who aren’t poor can’t be expected to live near poor people?

name: molly conger
tweet: i am having trouble understanding exactly what randolph means by that last comment about the presence of low income families over time leading to the entire complex becoming low income housing.

name: molly conger
tweet: dill asks about the financial counseling offered by habitat. habitat has staff that meet with families about financial planning and budgeting.

name: molly conger
tweet: “twenty minutes” fifty minutes ago    https://t.co/GtCze2xxw6

name: molly conger
tweet: “when they design their house, they can design a shed in the back,” the applicant says. the design plan also has a storage lot for work vehicles & trailers.

name: molly conger
tweet: rick please just allow this to move forward. vote no if you must but shut the fuck up.

name: molly conger
tweet: there are maybe 200 people here, many of whom want to give a public comment. rick has been dominating what was supposed to be a 20 minute presentation/Q&A with the application for an hour. he is being immensely disrespectful of this community.

tweet: god forbid you be able to see a building that contains poor people    https://t.co/tKT8kFZpnA

name: molly conger
tweet: liz palmer: “i’m disappointed that there’s not more in the code of development” planning for “those kinds of quality of life concerns.”  now on to the public hearing.

name: molly conger
tweet: first speaker is sunshine mathon, exec director of the piedmont housing alliance. resident led redevelopment is unique in “honoring and building upon the community’s rich history.” in his professional opinion, “you have an extraordinary plan in front of you.”

name: molly conger
tweet: next up is ron, a city resident & real estate attorney. he’s volunteered with habitat for years. in his 35 years as a real estate attorney, he says habitat for humanity is “the most creative and reliable developer of affordable housing in our community.”

name: molly conger
tweet: next speaker is from the community investment collaborative. he says he’s worried residents at the planning commission meeting were “mischaracterized” and was disappointed to hear their presence & decorum was negatively received.

name: molly conger
tweet: “please forgive any attendees’ lack of experience” in engaging with this process, he says. they’re just so excited about the project. (i wasn’t aware that anyone had negative things to say about the crowd at the last meeting! that’s really upsetting.)

name: molly conger
tweet: next speaker commends the board for the comprehensive plan & their commitment to revitalizing neighborhoods. “the habitat partnership is innovative, it’s out of the box” and partners with residents.

name: molly conger
tweet: a former habitat employee says this project started back in 2006. “the plan was always for it to be mixed use and mixed income.”    https://t.co/AEFJlqwzeI

name: molly conger
tweet: next speaker says the sunrise community (in my neighborhood!) is the only trailer park transformation in the country with zero resident displacement. it is a model & southwood can be just as successful.

name: molly conger
tweet: oh gross - here’s supervisor rick randolph’s facebook post criticizing the residents who attended the planning commission meeting   https://t.co/EityTjUnOT

name: molly conger
tweet: next up is a VERY pregnant @AnnieWords who says she should be home resting but is very passionate about this project.

name: molly conger
tweet: she is looking forward to moving her translating business out of her home and into the business space included in the development.

name: molly conger
tweet: her kids can’t flush toilet paper down the toilet. her heating bill is $500 in the winter. sometimes they all sleep in the living room to stay warm. they live in constant fear of storms & fire, both of which could easily kill her family.

name: molly conger
tweet: next speaker is a young southwood resident. she has lived there since 2009. she got her trailer for a great price and was originally upset that habitat wanted to take the trailers away,  but she realized she hates the way they live.

name: molly conger
tweet: next speaker is with the charlottesville low income housing coalition, which fully supports the southwood redevelopment.

name: molly conger
tweet: he calls this “a truly innovative way to tackle” our regional housing crisis. “habitat for humanity has a proven track record of providing affordable housing,” “they are not operating with some hidden ulterior motive.”

name: molly conger
tweet: “i would like to urge you all to take the risk,” “this is uncharted territory.” the southwood redevelopment is unique and could be a model for resident led redevelopment nationwide.

name: molly conger
tweet: “we want a place to live that is clean, safe, and peaceful.” the woman’s children grew up in southwood but are grown and gone now.

name: molly conger
tweet: a UVA student is reading a statement on behalf of an older woman she says is her mother figure here in virginia. (they look very sweet together!)

name: molly conger
tweet: infrastructure in the community desperately needs updating, “it is very uncomfortable to live like this. i share a septic tank with my neighbor and it is not nice.” water, sewer, stormwater drainage, and internet need to be improved and will be in the development.

name: molly conger
tweet: “these are not the plans of one sole person but of the whole community,” “if you like you can come to southwood and we can show you step by step how we came up with this plan.”

name: molly conger
tweet: the next speaker is reading a statement on behalf of a southwood resident who stands next to hear wearing the headsets provided to residents receiving real time spanish translation.

name: molly conger
tweet: the woman has attended FORTY SEVEN planning meetings for the redevelopment. her statement includes a sweet aside about her delicious homemade tortillas which draws chuckles and snaps from her neighbors in attendance. liz palmer scowls at the noise.

name: molly conger
tweet: she was recently interviewed for this piece in the washington post    https://t.co/XlPvSQlI6s

name: molly conger
tweet: the next speaker is reading a statement on behalf of a southwood resident. this statement too emphasizes how many planning meetings they’ve attended (50 meetings!) and their love of community & need for infrastructure improvements.

name: molly conger
tweet: my thumbs got behind, but the prior speaker also got in a jab at randolph’s repeated accusations that the residents want “many soccer fields,” saying “we want good homes” for our neighbors and green space. not “many soccer fields.”

name: molly conger
tweet: this speaker says having a house is her dream for her kids. she has worked on the redevelopment project for over two years.

name: molly conger
tweet: “no one just came and built something and said this is how it is,” “this project is part of us and we have the satisfaction that it is ours.” “it is our own, from our own minds.” “we may be poor, but with great desire to achieve the american dream.”

name: molly conger
tweet: the next speaker is an organizer with IMPACT. “the development proposed at southwood is a breath of fresh air,” and will increase affordable and mixed income housing. it not only improves housing for current residents, but builds new affordable units.

name: molly conger
tweet: “southwood has a wonderful community spirit and this redevelopment allows that spirit to shine,” she says.

name: molly conger
tweet: “i frankly wish all developers in our community were as proactive as habitat has been,” says the next speaker. he’s worked with habitat and the county engineer on environmental issues related to the project.

name: molly conger
tweet: next speaker is reading a statement on behalf of a 35 year southwood resident. she has attended 51 development meetings. “we have put in a lot of hours.”

name: molly conger
tweet: a young resident read a statement from her mother at the last meeting, but tonight is giving a statement of her own. “i always wanted a house with my little brother and my parents. i think other little kids want that too, but they can’t afford it.”

name: molly conger
tweet: the next speaker is addressing the board in spanish, with translation provided by an organizer from the redevelopment project.

name: molly conger

name: molly conger

name: molly conger
tweet: “yes we are worried about the many trees that will be felled, but we are also planning to plant many new trees.”

name: molly conger

name: molly conger
tweet: “if not habitat, who? if not southwood, where? if not now, when?” asks the next speaker, urging the board to vote yes on rezoning.

name: molly conger

name: molly conger

name: molly conger

name: molly conger
tweet: when i slipped out during the recess to go to the bathroom, i saw a nearby meeting room full of children. this is a community supporting each other, providing childcare so over 100 residents, stakeholders in this project, could be here for this meeting.

name: molly conger
tweet: back in session. liz palmer thanks “everybody for all the things they said tonight.” “i do want to clear up a couple of things,” she says. “this board has been working on this project for a long time.” “the board has committed almost $4mil of taxpayer money to this.”

name: molly conger
tweet: “i just want to make sure that everybody understands that we have made a very large commitment of taxpayer money to this project,” palmer says.

name: molly conger
tweet: “we would expect to have more information” palmer says, specifically about environmental issues & the buffer along old lynchburg. “there are more people involved” than the families who need new homes.

name: molly conger
tweet: “i hope that on phase 2, when that comes before the board, that we’re gonna see these things,” palmer says. she seems concerned that the applicant will keep to their word.

name: molly conger
tweet: supervisor normal dill says he is frustrated. “we approve holiday inns, we approve car dealerships expanding, we approve wawas coming in,” he says those businesses know the system. “we have such a unique opportunity here.”

name: molly conger
tweet: dill calls the stormwater concerns at this stage “a detail.” habitat has a strong track record as a reliable partner. “i’d much rather approve this and have some water issues then approve a business that’s selling petroleum products and junk food.”

name: molly conger
tweet: dill: “this is such an amazingly unique, wonderful process.” habitat has been working with southwood for almost 30 years, he says. “it’s financially strong, it helps so many people, it has an incredible cadre of volunteers,” “we should be ready to go.”

name: molly conger
tweet: ann mallek says all applicants should be held accountable for what’s presented at public meetings. “it’s difficult to look at plans,” (her comment is meandering and i’m not sure exactly what point she’s trying to make about the buildings in wickham pond being tall)

name: molly conger
tweet: “i really hope that if people have particular questions that they raise them now,” mallek says (well yes now is the time because you have to vote tonight)

name: molly conger
tweet: rick randolph, whose district this is in, starts out by quoting reagan, “trust but verify.” he says he hopes to reverse that be seeking to verify information that is not spelled out in the code of development (in what way is that the inverse of the quote?)

name: molly conger
tweet: randolph says he has ongoing questions about trees. he also wants more specifics on stormwater.

name: molly conger

name: molly conger
tweet: about the trees & the expectation that they should render the development invisible, county attorney greg kamptner says this is a development area. everyone living in the area should expect that the land across the street is going to be developed.

name: molly conger
tweet: randolph cannot fucking let this go. “the taxpayers in the future will pay to put in bus stops,” yeah, like they do in every community.

name: molly conger

name: molly conger

name: molly conger
tweet: surprisingly, randolph makes the motion to approve the rezoning. and it passes unanimously to a loud round of applause and cheers from the gallery. after 4.5 hours, there are still 100+ people here.

name: molly conger
tweet: there’s still a little meeting business to wrap up, but the crowd is slowly filtering out of chambers. people are cheering and embracing and laughing as they make their way out of the auditorium.

name: molly conger

name: molly conger
tweet: liz palmer is already standing up with her backpack on, signaling an intense desire for the meeting to end.

name: molly conger
tweet: i’m very glad they didn’t defer this vote to their next meeting because it is on my BIRTHDAY and i do not plan to spend my birthday with the albemarle county board of supervisors.   meeting adjourned.

name: molly conger
tweet: i know i say this kind of a lot and it’s really corny but i really do consider it an honor and a privilege to be able to record the stories of my community. the people who spoke at public comment tonight moved me to tears several times and i’m glad i could share this with you
